 application.<br/><br/><strong>Content aggregators:</strong> SingularDTV, Viuly, Viewly, DTube, PopChest and Lino have their distinctions, but their objective can basically be said to aggregate content and provide portals where fans can sponsor artists. In most cases, they are against advertising. Some of them are built on Ethereum; others on Steem; some are even built on Bitcoin.<br/><br/><strong>Mobile applications:</strong> Props (YouNow), Current and Flixxo are examples of mobile applications with a similar purpose to the ones listed above. However, they are developed by centralized, profit-minded companies, and incorporate fees on certain transactions in order to maintain themselves.<br/><br/><strong>Curation and governance:</strong> Lightstreams and Userfeeds propose solutions for organizing and recommending content, in a way that could be integrated into video platforms.<br/><br/>The way all these layers of technology can interact is still unclear. A couple of them might make up what we would call a “platform”. There are also cases in which half a dozen or more might intersect in a single platform. Many that seem identical are actually quite different (e.g. WebTorrent x IPFS). Also, some initiatives that aren’t currently integrated to the ones mentioned above might soon become part of the group, such as Bidio for advertisements and Userfeeds for recommendations.<br/><br/>We are still in the early steps of a journey that is gradually redesigning the panorama for video, content creation and online advertising. A market of two billion people awaits disintermediation. The path towards that goal demands collaboration, patience and experimentation."
